<subSubSection id="639E65491C0D5336558EFC572144E082" lastPageId="71" lastPageNumber="72" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" type="description">
<paragraph id="2B3B36C21C0D5337558EFC572074E403" blockId="70.[151,1437,793,1288]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0D5337558EFC572242E39C" bold="true" box="[199,337,973,999]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Description</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0D53375428FC57228DE39C" box="[353,414,973,999]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Adult</emphasis>
. Occipital protuberance absent. Wing: R 
<subScript id="B70034871C0D53375622FC7A2060E395" attach="left" box="[875,883,992,1006]" fontSize="6" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">5</subScript>
nearly straight, joining C anteriad of wing apex, C broken at juncture with R 
<subScript id="B70034871C0D53375492FB9E22F0E469" attach="left" box="[475,483,1028,1042]" fontSize="6" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">5</subScript>
, Rs not present [
<figureCitation id="B3BF2A471C0D533757E0FC6B2018E477" box="[681,779,1009,1036]" captionStart="FIGURES 41" captionStartId="70.[151,264,1892,1916]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,1324,1846]" captionTargetId="figure-367@70.[151,1436,1309,1866]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 41a–h. “Calopedila” polyalthiae: a, galls on Polyalthia subcordata (Fig. 293 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926)); b, pupal vertex and antennal bases; c–g, female: c, palpus; d, tarsal claw and empodium; e, wing; f, postabdomen (lateral); g, 10th flagellomere; h, male 7th flagellomere." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406956" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406956/files/figure.png" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Fig. 41e</figureCitation>
] Irregular number of flagellar segments, first and second flagellomeres not connate, 17–18 (n= 
<quantity id="EC7C9B271C0D53375770FB8F2170E454" box="[569,611,1045,1071]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.62" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" unit="in" value="3.0">3 in</quantity>
male, cylindrical and short-necked [
<figureCitation id="B3BF2A471C0D533756B1FB8F2748E44B" box="[1016,1115,1045,1072]" captionStart="FIGURES 41" captionStartId="70.[151,264,1892,1916]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,1324,1846]" captionTargetId="figure-367@70.[151,1436,1309,1866]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 41a–h. “Calopedila” polyalthiae: a, galls on Polyalthia subcordata (Fig. 293 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926)); b, pupal vertex and antennal bases; c–g, female: c, palpus; d, tarsal claw and empodium; e, wing; f, postabdomen (lateral); g, 10th flagellomere; h, male 7th flagellomere." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406956" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406956/files/figure.png" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Fig. 41h</figureCitation>
], and 19 (n=1) flagellomeres in female with very short necks [
<figureCitation id="B3BF2A471C0D53375759FBA32164E42F" box="[528,631,1081,1108]" captionStart="FIGURES 41" captionStartId="70.[151,264,1892,1916]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,1324,1846]" captionTargetId="figure-367@70.[151,1436,1309,1866]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 41a–h. “Calopedila” polyalthiae: a, galls on Polyalthia subcordata (Fig. 293 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926)); b, pupal vertex and antennal bases; c–g, female: c, palpus; d, tarsal claw and empodium; e, wing; f, postabdomen (lateral); g, 10th flagellomere; h, male 7th flagellomere." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406956" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406956/files/figure.png" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
Fig. 
<quantity id="EC7C9B271C0D5337570EFBA32164E42F" box="[583,631,1081,1108]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="4.1" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" unit="g" value="41.0">41g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
]. Palpus 3-segmented, palpiger present [
<figureCitation id="B3BF2A471C0D5337510BFBA327B5E42F" box="[1090,1190,1081,1108]" captionStart="FIGURES 41" captionStartId="70.[151,264,1892,1916]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,1324,1846]" captionTargetId="figure-367@70.[151,1436,1309,1866]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 41a–h. “Calopedila” polyalthiae: a, galls on Polyalthia subcordata (Fig. 293 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926)); b, pupal vertex and antennal bases; c–g, female: c, palpus; d, tarsal claw and empodium; e, wing; f, postabdomen (lateral); g, 10th flagellomere; h, male 7th flagellomere." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406956" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406956/files/figure.png" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Fig. 41c</figureCitation>
]. Tarsal claws bent at midlength, robust, toothed, empodia as long as claws [
<figureCitation id="B3BF2A471C0D533757BEFBC7204FE403" box="[759,860,1117,1144]" captionStart="FIGURES 41" captionStartId="70.[151,264,1892,1916]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,1324,1846]" captionTargetId="figure-367@70.[151,1436,1309,1866]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 41a–h. “Calopedila” polyalthiae: a, galls on Polyalthia subcordata (Fig. 293 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926)); b, pupal vertex and antennal bases; c–g, female: c, palpus; d, tarsal claw and empodium; e, wing; f, postabdomen (lateral); g, 10th flagellomere; h, male 7th flagellomere." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406956" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406956/files/figure.png" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Fig. 41d</figureCitation>
].
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2B3B36C21C0D5337558EFB1B2193E4C4" blockId="70.[151,1437,793,1288]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0D5337558EFB1B2212E4E0" box="[199,257,1153,1179]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Male</emphasis>
. Wing 
<quantity id="EC7C9B271C0D5337541FFB1B22BEE4E7" box="[342,429,1153,1180]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" unit="mm" value="2.4">2.4 mm</quantity>
(2.4–2.5) long, 
<quantity id="EC7C9B271C0D5337572FFB1B21ADE4E7" box="[614,702,1153,1180]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" unit="mm" value="1.1">1.1 mm</quantity>
(1.0–1.1) wide. Terminalia not properly observable on available specimens; gonostylus completely setulose.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2B3B36C21C0D5337558EFB532614E573" blockId="70.[151,1437,793,1288]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0D5337558EFB532208E498" box="[199,283,1225,1251]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Female</emphasis>
. Wing 3.0 mm (2.9–3.0) long, 
<quantity id="EC7C9B271C0D533757CDFB5321CEE49F" box="[644,733,1225,1252]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" unit="mm" value="1.2">1.2 mm</quantity>
wide. Terminalia: elongate, protractible, cerci fused, tapered, more than 2x longer than basal width, hypoproct narrow in lateral view, 1/3 length of cerci [
<figureCitation id="B3BF2A471C0D533751D5FB7727EFE573" box="[1180,1276,1261,1288]" captionStart="FIGURES 41" captionStartId="70.[151,264,1892,1916]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,1324,1846]" captionTargetId="figure-367@70.[151,1436,1309,1866]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 41a–h. “Calopedila” polyalthiae: a, galls on Polyalthia subcordata (Fig. 293 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926)); b, pupal vertex and antennal bases; c–g, female: c, palpus; d, tarsal claw and empodium; e, wing; f, postabdomen (lateral); g, 10th flagellomere; h, male 7th flagellomere." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406956" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406956/files/figure.png" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Fig. 41f</figureCitation>
].
</paragraph>
<caption id="7FFB664A1C0D533755DEF8FE22F1E7BF" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406956" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4406956" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406956/files/figure.png" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" startId="70.[151,264,1892,1916]" targetBox="[165,1421,1324,1846]" targetPageId="70">
<paragraph id="2B3B36C21C0D533755DEF8FE22F1E7BF" blockId="70.[151,1436,1892,1988]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0D533755DEF8FE2177E707" bold="true" box="[151,612,1892,1916]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
FIGURES 41a–h. “ 
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0D53375425F8FE2177E707" bold="true" box="[364,612,1892,1916]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
<taxonomicName id="EC844D411C0D53375425F8FE22CFE707" authorityName="Kieffer" authorityYear="1913" box="[364,476,1892,1916]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Calopedila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Calopedila</taxonomicName>
” 
<taxonomicName id="EC844D411C0D533754B8F8FE2177E707" box="[497,612,1892,1916]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Calopedila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="polyalthiae">polyalthiae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</emphasis>
: a, galls on 
<taxonomicName id="EC844D411C0D533757AFF8FE20DAE707" box="[742,969,1892,1916]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Polyalthia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subcordata">
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0D533757AFF8FE20DAE707" box="[742,969,1892,1916]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Polyalthia subcordata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 293 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926)); b, pupal vertex and antennal bases; c–g, female: c, palpus; d, tarsal claw and empodium; e, wing; f, postabdomen (lateral); g, 10 
<superScript id="DCF19B8A1C0D53375000F8122647E7ED" attach="left" box="[1353,1364,1928,1942]" fontSize="6" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">th</superScript>
flagellomere; h, male 7 
<superScript id="DCF19B8A1C0D53375401F8362240E7C1" attach="left" box="[328,339,1964,1978]" fontSize="6" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">th</superScript>
flagellomere.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="2B3B36C21C0C5336558EFF0D2144E082" blockId="71.[151,1437,150,862]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0C5336558EFF0D2211E0CB" box="[199,258,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Pupa</emphasis>
[
<figureCitation id="B3BF2A471C0C53365458FF0D2266E0CA" box="[273,373,150,177]" captionStart="FIGURES 41" captionStartId="70.[151,264,1892,1916]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,1324,1846]" captionTargetId="figure-367@70.[151,1436,1309,1866]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 41a–h. “Calopedila” polyalthiae: a, galls on Polyalthia subcordata (Fig. 293 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926)); b, pupal vertex and antennal bases; c–g, female: c, palpus; d, tarsal claw and empodium; e, wing; f, postabdomen (lateral); g, 10th flagellomere; h, male 7th flagellomere." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406956" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406956/files/figure.png" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Fig. 41b</figureCitation>
]. Cervical setae short, less than half-length of antennal horns. Antennal horns elongate, in ventral view narrowed by half at distal third, resulting in an acutely pointed lateral lobe and a terminal, rounded apical lobe. Prothoracic spiracle short, narrow.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="639E65491C0C5336558EFE992054E2FE" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="2B3B36C21C0C5336558EFE992054E2FE" blockId="71.[151,1437,150,862]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0C5336558EFE992227E166" bold="true" box="[199,308,259,285]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="4F154B331C0C5336540CFE9922C1E165" author="Felt, E. P." box="[325,466,259,286]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="385 - 389" refId="ref58265" refString="Felt, E. P. (1927 b) New species of East Indian gall midges. Treubia, 9, 385 - 389." type="journal article" year="1927">Felt (1927b)</bibRefCitation>
placed this species only tentatively in 
<taxonomicName id="EC844D411C0C533656DCFE992702E166" authorityName="Kieffer" authorityYear="1913" box="[917,1041,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Calopedila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0C533656DCFE992702E166" box="[917,1041,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Calopedila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a genus erected for 
<taxonomicName id="EC844D411C0C5336504EFE99229FE13A" authority="(Kieffer 1903)" baseAuthorityName="Kieffer" baseAuthorityYear="1903" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Rhopalomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="herbsti">
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0C5336504EFE9923F6E13A" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Rhopalomyia herbsti</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="4F154B331C0C533655BBFEBD2297E13A" author="Kieffer, J. - J." box="[242,388,295,321]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="226 - 228" refId="ref59850" refString="Kieffer, J. - J. (1903) Description de cecidomyies nouvelles du Chili. Revista Chilena de Historia Natural, 7, 226 - 228." type="journal article" year="1903">Kieffer 1903</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
that causes a branch gall on 
<taxonomicName id="EC844D411C0C53365781FEBD20F2E13A" box="[712,993,295,321]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Baccharis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rosmarinifolia">
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0C53365781FEBD20F2E13A" box="[712,993,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Baccharis rosmarinifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="EC844D411C0C533656A7FEBD277FE13A" box="[1006,1132,295,321]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
) in 
<collectingCountry id="539376521C0C533651DFFEBD27C5E13A" box="[1174,1238,295,321]" name="Chile" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Chile</collectingCountry>
. The Chilean species has tarsal claws with small teeth and empodia that are nearly twice the length of the claws, male flagellomeres without necks, and female cerci that are no longer than broad. From these characters 
<taxonomicName id="EC844D411C0C5336512FFEF527F1E1F2" authorityName="Kieffer" authorityYear="1913" box="[1126,1250,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Calopedila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0C5336512FFEF527F1E1F2" box="[1126,1250,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Calopedila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to have an affinity to 
<taxonomicName id="EC844D411C0C5336547AFE092147E1D6" authority="Rubsaamen" authorityName="Rubsaamen" authorityYear="1892" box="[307,596,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Rhopalomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0C5336547AFE0922DBE1D6" box="[307,456,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Rhopalomyia</emphasis>
Rübsaamen
</taxonomicName>
and is treated as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="EC844D411C0C53365147FE0923F6E1AA" authority="in Gagne &amp; Jaschhof (2017)" authorityName="in Gagne &amp; Jaschhof" authorityYear="2017" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Rhopalomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0C53365147FE0927B0E1D6" box="[1038,1187,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Rhopalomyia</emphasis>
in 
<bibRefCitation id="4F154B331C0C53365183FE0923F6E1AA" author="Gagne, R. J. &amp; Jaschhof, M." pageId="71" pageNumber="72" refId="ref58587" refString="Gagne, R. J. &amp; Jaschhof, M. (2017) A Catalog of the Cecidomyiidae (Diptera) of the World. 4 th Edition. Digital. U. S. Department of Agriculture, c / o Smithsonian Institution, Washington, D. C. Available from: https: // www. ars. usda. gov / ARSUser- Files / 80420580 / Gagne _ 2014 _ World _ Cecidomyiidae _ Catalog _ 3 rd _ Edition. pdf (accessed 23 December 2019)" type="book" year="2017">Gagné &amp; Jaschhof (2017)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. “ 
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0C533655B4FE2D211CE1AA" box="[253,527,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<taxonomicName id="EC844D411C0C533655B4FE2D226CE1AA" authorityName="Kieffer" authorityYear="1913" box="[253,383,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Calopedila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Calopedila</taxonomicName>
” 
<taxonomicName id="EC844D411C0C533654D8FE2D211CE1AA" box="[401,527,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Calopedila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="polyalthiae">polyalthiae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is shown here to have tarsal claws with large teeth and empodia that are only as long as the claws [
<figureCitation id="B3BF2A471C0C53365429FE4122D0E18E" box="[352,451,474,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 41" captionStartId="70.[151,264,1892,1916]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,1324,1846]" captionTargetId="figure-367@70.[151,1436,1309,1866]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 41a–h. “Calopedila” polyalthiae: a, galls on Polyalthia subcordata (Fig. 293 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926)); b, pupal vertex and antennal bases; c–g, female: c, palpus; d, tarsal claw and empodium; e, wing; f, postabdomen (lateral); g, 10th flagellomere; h, male 7th flagellomere." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406956" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406956/files/figure.png" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Fig. 41d</figureCitation>
], male flagellomeres with necks [
<figureCitation id="B3BF2A471C0C5336567BFE412086E18E" box="[818,917,474,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 41" captionStartId="70.[151,264,1892,1916]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,1324,1846]" captionTargetId="figure-367@70.[151,1436,1309,1866]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 41a–h. “Calopedila” polyalthiae: a, galls on Polyalthia subcordata (Fig. 293 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926)); b, pupal vertex and antennal bases; c–g, female: c, palpus; d, tarsal claw and empodium; e, wing; f, postabdomen (lateral); g, 10th flagellomere; h, male 7th flagellomere." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406956" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406956/files/figure.png" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Fig. 41h</figureCitation>
], and female cerci that are elongate and narrow [
<figureCitation id="B3BF2A471C0C533655D7FE6523EEE262" box="[158,253,510,537]" captionStart="FIGURES 41" captionStartId="70.[151,264,1892,1916]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,1324,1846]" captionTargetId="figure-367@70.[151,1436,1309,1866]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 41a–h. “Calopedila” polyalthiae: a, galls on Polyalthia subcordata (Fig. 293 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926)); b, pupal vertex and antennal bases; c–g, female: c, palpus; d, tarsal claw and empodium; e, wing; f, postabdomen (lateral); g, 10th flagellomere; h, male 7th flagellomere." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406956" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406956/files/figure.png" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Fig. 41f</figureCitation>
], all of which show that the species was initially misplaced to genus. The species belongs to the supertribe 
<taxonomicName id="EC844D411C0C533655DEFDB92232E246" authorityName="Rubsaamen &amp; Hedicke" authorityYear="1926" box="[151,289,547,573]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="superTribe" superTribe="Lasiopteridi">Lasiopteridi</taxonomicName>
, but we cannot guess where this species might be assigned below that level given the poor specimens available and the fact that so little is known of SE Asian 
<taxonomicName id="EC844D411C0C53365645FDDD2080E21A" authorityName="Rubsaamen &amp; Hedicke" authorityYear="1926" box="[780,915,583,609]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="superTribe" superTribe="Lasiopteridi">Lasiopteridi</taxonomicName>
generally. We might feel justified in erecting a new genus for “ 
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0C53365400FDF122E4E2FE" box="[329,503,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
C.” 
<taxonomicName id="EC844D411C0C53365430FDF122E4E2FE" box="[377,503,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Calopedila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="polyalthiae">polyalthiae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
once better material is found.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="639E65491C0C5336558EFD1421C3E36E" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="2B3B36C21C0C5336558EFD1421C3E36E" blockId="71.[151,1437,150,862]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0C5336558EFD142232E2D3" bold="true" box="[199,289,654,680]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Biology</emphasis>
. This species causes a fruit gall on 
<taxonomicName id="EC844D411C0C533657F5FD1520A5E2D2" box="[700,950,655,681]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Polyalthia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subcordata">
<emphasis id="19F0EAD01C0C533657F5FD1520A5E2D2" box="[700,950,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Polyalthia subcordata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="EC844D411C0C5336568FFD152747E2D2" box="[966,1108,655,681]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Annonaceae</taxonomicName>
) described by DvLR &amp; DvL 1926, gall No. 408, Fig. 293 [
<figureCitation id="B3BF2A471C0C533654A1FD29215FE2B6" box="[488,588,690,717]" captionStart="FIGURES 41" captionStartId="70.[151,264,1892,1916]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,1324,1846]" captionTargetId="figure-367@70.[151,1436,1309,1866]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 41a–h. “Calopedila” polyalthiae: a, galls on Polyalthia subcordata (Fig. 293 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926)); b, pupal vertex and antennal bases; c–g, female: c, palpus; d, tarsal claw and empodium; e, wing; f, postabdomen (lateral); g, 10th flagellomere; h, male 7th flagellomere." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406956" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406956/files/figure.png" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Fig. 41a</figureCitation>
]). Individual galls are spheroid, about 
<quantity id="EC7C9B271C0C53365148FD292750E2B6" box="[1025,1091,691,717]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
across and covered with short brown hairs. They develop on the surface of the fruit, occurring mostly gregariously and arranged in thick irregular clumps. The larval chamber is small and spherical.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
